segments.text: ...cost for those displaced as a result of urban renewal.
Could you continue with that, please?
Under the university eminent domain proceedings, apparently there would not have been a relocation cost that would enter into it.
And by going the urban renewal route, this meant that the people would get payment for a relocation.
And that was one of the reasons that urban renewal was used.

Can you see areas of the city that were impacted by this as a result of influx of those that were displaced and let's say a demand on services that had not been anticipated as a result of urban renewal programs and had to be planned for?
I don't recall
a specific area that was impacted as a result.
We did have individuals who were displaced, and I think it was very difficult for some of them to find comparable property that they could afford.
Now, some of the areas in the university area, we had a number of elderly widows.
I don't know why, but this tends to happen that way,
who had converted their residences to boarding houses and apartments, and it was their primary livelihood.
Now, a number of them did not go into or continue that occupation as they were displaced.
In other words, other arrangements were made, and that was discontinued.
So I do think that we affected individuals, but I don't think that
the population was that so great that we had a mass exodus or group that impacted any other section of town to any extensive degree.
Which sections of Austin would you say people would mainly relocate in as a result of their limited incomes?
Well, in the university area, I would say that a number of the people would go into apartments.
Some of them, I'm sure, went to live with families.
I do know of some who just moved to, say, duplexes and this sort of thing.
The community development program of the federal government, mid-1970s to present, how has this affected planning in Austin?
I don't think that I can answer that question adequately today.
The freeway era, especially the interstate highway system of mid-1950s and that had major impact in cities in changing transportation routes, in many cities increasing suburbanization and that.
What planning was involved to deal with the fallout from this type of program in Austin?
Well, actually, we had tremendous
advantage when Interstate 35 was put in.
We had East Avenue in that general location, and it initially was about 200 feet wide.
And so the initial construction on Interstate was within that right of way.
The later construction, it was, as you know, that these projects are almost out of date by the time that you start implementing them because of population growth and so on.
So the northern section was built with 200 feet of right-of-way.
Then the midsection, which was through the Bracken Ridge area and on south, it was discovered that really they needed more right-of-way, so more right-of-way was acquired.
But because of having 200 to begin with, it wasn't, you know,
as bad as it might have been.
Then as the traffic need increased, it was discovered that we could not stay within that 200 feet.
We needed extra area for extra lanes.
And at that time, the Highway Department looked at the land cost versus construction cost, and it was determined that they would go with a double deck.
because the land costs apparently were higher than the construction costs.
So that's what resulted in the double-deck of interstate.
Now, of course, we do have continued expansion north end and south end on interstate and where the right-of-way can be acquired for
apparently less than the double-decking.
We're going with the surface, more or less.
As far as the urban area extending on out as a result, or you might call it suburban, as a result of the expressways, we've had really only one expressway, and that's Interstate 35.
We have a number of other major arterioles, but most of those are really overburdened, and they need to be expressed ways.
183 is virtually a nightmare because of all the development that we've had that has gone on out.
And Austin, contrary to some of the things that you will find in the new comprehensive plan where people state that they want to establish
land development that would support a mass transit system or bus system, whatever, anyway, a type of mass transit.
Each time anybody comes in with a proposal for any sort of high density, be it apartments, high rise, anything of that sort, we have tremendous opposition.
from the abutting neighborhoods.
They do not want high density residential.
They feel as though that they want single family.
And even in areas, they don't want duplexes even.
They object to townhouses.
In other words, single family is what everybody seems to want.
And everybody can't afford it.
But the people who are already there, they say, we want to keep this the way it is.
And the people who are coming in, they need housing.
And we have a difficult situation.
And I'm not sure whether we have any good solution for it, because there are times when you want mass transit.
You need higher intensity development in order to support mass transit.
The further out you go, the more you have the need for the mass transit, but if you have such low density, mass transit can't support itself.
So we have a situation that I don't think has a good answer.
How did the location of Interstate 35 itself, its position in the city, affect developmental patterns as far as residences and businesses went?
Was there any kind of partitioning by income groups, ethnic groups, or anything like that that you can see as a result of Interstate 35?
I don't think it was as a result of Interstate 35.
I feel as though that we had the...
pattern already set before interstate ever came in.
East Austin has been predominantly minority and West Austin and some minority in South Austin, but it has generally been on the east side.
And I think part of the reason for this is that as the transportation system changed from railroad to other forms of transportation, the affluent moved away from the East Austin area
And this housing then became available.
It was a little lower priced.
And so I think the minorities tended to move into that area.
And it just developed this way.
A filtering process, you'd say.
Yes.
What significant public development projects or private development projects can you think of have impacted planning in Austin?
University of Texas is a major industry.
That has impacted Austin tremendously in more ways than one.
The street system, because of the fact that they have continued to expand, we continue to vacate streets.
In other words, they form kind of a big barrier or block.
in right north of the core area.
The taxing situation, it has affected that because we have over 50% of the land within the city of Austin is tax-exempt because it's either university, state, church, federal, county.
And so this does affect Austin quite a bit.
And its tax base.
And its tax base.
The other things...
We have, of course, Bergstrom, which has impacted to a degree.

You don't stop and think about some of these impacts as much when they've been here a long time, because you have learned to integrate it into the community, and you just don't really think about the impact.
Then, of course, we've had industries that have come in.
But until just fairly recent years, we didn't have any major industries here.
We had the university, I think, and the state capital were the two major industries in Austin as far as employment was concerned.
That's another reason, of course, our economy has been as stable as it has been because we have not been dependent on the market as such as far as goods are concerned.
And that is changing because we've had more industry here, but we have what we would consider
the higher quality industries, the clean industries, and this is what has been encouraged for Austin.
And, of course, one of the reasons for that is the university.

So we go back to the influence of the university because a lot of the technological industries like to move here because they have a source of drawing from employees from the university, which, of course, has benefited us.
What is the positioning of these so-called clean industries in Austin?
Are they fairly, do they remain clustered in a particular area of town?
Can you characterize it in that sense?
I don't think we can do it.
Quite in that way, we do have several industries out northwest.
They wanted acreages.
Most of the industries that have come in have not wanted to move into the areas that we had laid out basically for industry in the original 1961 plan.
Can you see reasons for that?
Yes.
It's because as soon as people felt as though their land was classified for industry, they boosted the price.
And they felt, here we have an industrial price.
So when the industries came in, they started looking for other land that was not classified for industry, and they could get it for a lot less.
And that's exactly what happened.
And you found that the industries, of course, would move wherever they found land was the least expensive.
Transportation was not as important a factor.
Well, all of them have considered transportation, too.
All of them have not considered terrain because one of the things that in the 1961 plan, the industries that we had established and some of them have followed through in these areas very well.
We had located them where our terrain was fairly level, where we had rail service, where we had major streets.
Those areas, a lot of them are developing for industry, like we had anticipated.
But we have had a good bit of pressure on for industry in other areas as well.
How have state projects, new construction, new state office buildings in the capital area impacted planning in the city of Austin by taking available land space, other than the taxing problem?
Of course, in the 61 plan, we had anticipated that the capital would expand all the way from 11th Street to 19th Street.
And we had worked with the state at that time, and they did make plans on what their expansion would be.
One of the things that I think has affected the community, and that is that
We do not have control over zoning control over state buildings.
And so heist limitations, that sort of thing, they can do as they please.
And we do, or we have ended up with some buildings that have a certain tendency to block the capital view.
to a degree, but of course we have private buildings under the zoning jurisdiction that also do the same.
Have height restrictions been considered in the area in order that the capital view may be preserved?
Oh yes, that is I think going to be one of the upcoming major issues.
We have had a number of high-rise proposals within the past year, and
There's been more and more concern expressed by various groups and citizens in regard to keeping the visibility of the capital protected.
It's a very difficult situation because Austin is hilly.
There are some areas that maybe you could have a fairly tall high rise that would not affect.
the line of vision from major parts of the city.
Then there are other areas that if you have prominent locations, or as far as height would be concerned, the relationship, even a fairly low-rise building could block.
So we are working on this to a degree at the present time.
It's going to take some time to develop
the visual corridor plan.
But again, that is something that will be coming up.

Has the land that's been taken up by the state government as a result of capital expansion and university expansion resulted in a squeeze in land space that is needed for commercial facilities and residential facilities for the employees and the influx of population that's resulted?
I don't think that it really has affected it in that way.
The downtown area, there's a lot of available land
I should not say land.
There are a number of older buildings that are not being used to capacity.
We have a number of areas that need to be revitalized that are not being used to their full optimum.
I don't believe that the university and state expansion has really affected the commercial development.
Now, you mentioned earlier that it's only been in recent years that a number of industries have been attracted to the area, and most of them have been so-called light industries.
Have heavy industries ever played a role in planning in Austin, or do you think they might in the future?
We had one, and that was when Michelin, the entire company, planned to come in with a plant.
This was when, pardon?
about a year and a half to two years ago.
Not very long ago.
They had selected a site.
Accessibility was a little bit of a problem.
However, the development of the industry would not have generated much more traffic than residential development of the same site.
But there was a fear on the part of
most of the surrounding subdivisions, existing subdivisions, that it would create tremendous environmental problems.
Whenever you think about a tire company, you think about the worst part of the tire company, the odors and everything.
The Michelin company was very, very secretive in their proposal in the early stages.
They did not come in and do any
groundwork as far as preparing neighborhoods or meeting with neighborhoods.
They got information as far as availability of utilities and, you know, a number of things, technical questions had been asked.
And we had reviewed it in that sense without knowing what sort of industry was being proposed.
So when they made the announcement, there was an immediate negative response.
attitude and feeling on the part of the public.

And even though they did fly a number of people, including I think some of the neighborhood leaders, to some of the plants that functioned in a comparable way, and the feeling was still so negative that they just dropped the project.
How have other major commercial investments played a part in planning in Austin?
Major commercial or let's say residential subdivisions or developments like that, how have they played a part in planning in Austin?
I'm not exactly sure how to answer that.
We have some developers who are very, very large and they develop
Certain areas, they have a tendency to go into areas that can be served easily, that are lower in cost so that the housing ends up being lower.
They can develop for a lower price.
And one thing that we've had a problem on, and that is that the new comprehensive plan established a north-south growth corridor.
In some of those areas, the utilities are not there.
The concept was that the city would encourage the development in these areas by participating by means of CIP in bringing services to the area and so on.
The other areas, the growth areas that were supposed to be protected and discouraged, we were not to deny the development of those areas, but we were not to participate
and provide any funding for these other areas.
Unfortunately, some of the areas that are in the more sensitive environmentally situated locations are the ones that are very desirable for housing.
They have the views.
In other words,
Some of them are in the more affluent areas.
It costs more to develop, but that's where a lot of people want to live.
And those are the most environmentally sensitive at the same time.
That's right, and that's where the people would like to live.
And so we have pressures on because the developers are responding to the market, and the market is there, and so they want to develop those areas.

Can you think of specific development projects that were large enough in scale that, in and of themselves, they had a significant impact on planning as a result of transportation, utility needs, or expansion?
Are you talking about housing or industry or both?
Well, both, I would imagine, especially residential, let's say.
Residential?
Well, we've had some, well, just like in that 183 corridor.
We've had a series of subdivisions that have moved into that area.
And part of it is a result of Texas Instruments going in and IBM in the Northwest sector.
And so housing wants to be a little bit closer to places of employment.
So they kind of go together a little bit, and so we've had a lot of pressure on that area, and of course it affects the street system.

Well, I'm not going to say it's overloaded, but it's over text, and with the speeds that people travel, whether they're within the speed limit or not, we've ended up with a fairly dangerous situation.
We have

a number of subdivisions that have gone into various areas where the streets are not really up to standard that might create problems as the subdivision developed because with the capital improvement program needs for some of these streets, just like our last bond election didn't make it, so we did not have the funding for upgrading of some of the facilities that needed to be upgraded.
So we are ending up with some developments that are on streets that are not really adequate.
And not designed for that kind of capacity.

I mean, the plans were there in relation to the arterial system, but the timing had not been reached because of either the capital improvements program or the bond election not making it or the fact that there is always a time lag
What significant changes in the city charter have impacted the administration of planning in Austin?
There haven't been any major changes that would have impacted us, in my opinion.
Are there any charter changes that would have significantly impacted plan implementation?
Different types of zoning allowed?
Well, not, I don't think, within the charter.
Now, I think, I'm trying to remember what proposals came up
there have been some discussions on modifying the charter and I think that with if we end up having area planning
And if that should go through sector planning, that would impact our department tremendously, because we would not have the staff to function in this way.
Could you briefly describe on what basis these sectors would be delineated in that?
Well, this is the other problem on exactly what boundaries would be established.
But I'm assuming that it would be established
based on physical barriers.
And I don't think that we have the definition, say, for neighborhood, even though a lot of people call themselves a neighborhood group.
We don't have the traditional definition of a neighborhood anymore.
What is a neighborhood?
I can't answer you anymore.
We used to use
long ago, really the service area of, say, an elementary school.
But with all our cross busing, that's gone out the window.
We do have some areas that are physically separated by creeks, by major thoroughfares, by a major public holding of land.
There are various things like that that might establish an area or a neighborhood
But when we talk about either sector planning or neighborhood planning, I think that our definition is a little bit loose.
And the areas would have to be set up.
It could be set up, say, almost in quadrants for the city, in four quadrants.
But on what line we would use, whether we would use, say, Lake Austin and Town Lake as one of the major boundaries, I'm sure that we would because I think it would be a logical one.
Interstate 35 would be another fairly good barrier because...
We do not have as much neighborhood association across those major barriers.
What administrative changes within the planning department can you see since you've been working here?
have impacted planning for Austin in its history?
Well, of course, the planning department was once a part of Public Works.
It separated off.
Do you know about when it was that it separated off?
I think that it was in the late 40s, or 48, 50, right in through there.
The fact that our Planning Commission makeup has changed the way that we function has changed a little.
We have realigned as the needs came up within the department because we have changed from
just one department and developed into sections.

The sections have changed because we used to have an engineering section that was dropped out and actually the engineering section covered the drafting and the drafting ended up under current planning.
So we have realigned depending on the needs of the community.
How have changes in directorship of the planning department itself over the years changed the
personality or changed the operations of the planning department?
I don't think there has been too great a change.
We've had, I think, very dedicated directors who are dedicated to the community, to the keeping the community environmentally
Well, clean.
We have concern for existing neighborhoods, residences.
This is one thing that has been consistent throughout.
I think it's really been fairly consistent now because of the implementation of the various plans under different directors.
There's been some transitional change, but I think that under our current director, there has been, I would say, the encouragement of public involvement.
getting everybody to become involved, to participate in the planning process.
And I think that this has happened under the current director, primarily.
What contributions can you see that were made by past directors, those preceding Mr. Lilly?
Well, we haven't had very many directors.
In fact, I think the first director was very, very involved in the development of Town Lake.
What was his name?
I wish you hadn't asked me that at this point.
I'll give it to you now.
To the best of your recollection then, who was the first planning director with the department here?
I believe the first one was Bill Parker.
And that was before you were employed here?
Yes.
from seeing his contributions to the department and what he had left with the department.
Can you see that his style of administration in the department impacted planning changes in comparison to his successor?
I don't think that anymore, because I think that he was a dedicated planner.
And he wanted the best for the community.
He had a strong interest in the improvement and development of the... Actually, it was Colorado River at that time because we didn't have the lake, Town Lake, but all the riverfront.
And it wasn't until recently that we had...
